 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Fazzeel</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Necros really don't get a choice of religion (you cannot be Agnostic, btw).  Only humans really have a choice, and that choice decides your starting city.  Religion has some faction consequences, but nothing you can control.  With the new newbie rules, starting a necro would not be as bad now as when I first started, so go for it...</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Moomu</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> I play a gnome necro on a PVP server and I could start all over again I would still probably stick with a gnome.  The reasons I went with a gnome are many...and a few people might not agree with some of them, but here goes.</P><P>Gnomes hide well.  This may not be important on a blue (non-pvp) server, but it is nice.  Faction...I do not have problems in most places.  As a necro, you are going to be KOS in some places...that is part of being a necro.  Gnomes have nice dex and agi, thus my melee skills went up nicely.  If you think that is not important...wait until you are 45th lvl and see how hard a mob hits you when your defense is not maxed out (they still hit hard, but I can tank for short durations.)</P><P>Iksars do have regen...but being the most hated race/class combo in the entire game can be quite annoying at times.  I feel it is much more enjoyable to have a race/class combo that can visit other cities, use other merchants, etc.  As a lizzy necro, everyone will want to pound your head in that is not a lizzy too...there are some exceptions.  I would not go with a lizzy as a newb...or ever, but that is just my opinion.</P><P>Only Erudites have enough of an intelligence boost to mention.  The int difference between Dark Elves and Gnomes is 1 point (134 vs 133.)  So, I do not see how people can claim that dark elves have better starting stats.</P><P>Both dark elves and gnomes can see in the dark; dark elves get hide which is nice...but they need it since they are so hated.  I have never regretted not having hide, and there are some nice items in game that give insta-invis anyway which is much more reliable than hide.</P><P>Dark Elves are liked in their home cities, but Gnomes are not.  That does not matter much since the people you need to like you are your guild leaders and spell vendors...who really cares if you are loved by the rest of your city.</P><P>And last, but not least...dark elf necromancers are a dime a dozen.  There are a decent amount of gnome necros, but not nearly as many as as there are dark elves.  If you see a dark elf, half the time you are looking at a necro.</P><P>One more thing...the int difference between erudites (high is 142) and gnomes (high is 133) is not so much that a few pieces of gear can not make up the difference later in the game when more int acutally influences your amount of mana.</P><P>The int/mana thing works like this:</P><P>@lvl50 1int = 10mana<BR>@lvl45 1int = 9mana<BR>@lvl40 1int = 8mana<BR>35 = 7mana<BR>30 = 6mana<BR>25 = 5mana<BR>20 = 4mana<BR>15 = 3mana<BR>10 = 2mana<BR>5 = 1mana</P><P>So, int does equal more mana...later.  Early on you wont see much of a difference between an int of 142 and 133.  At lvl 40 9int is a 72 mana difference.  That can be a lot or a little depending on how well you plan your encounters.  My gnome has always had enough mana since I plan carefully.</P><P>At level 60, the regen of an iksar might be very nice...but with the exp penalty (I hate exping, I like to play) leveling will be a bit slower...but you are still hated by the entire world.</P><P>Gnomes will rule the world.</P><P>The best thing to do when trying to trouble shoot pc issues is to try and remember the last thing you did before it started acting strangely, then empty a clip from a .45 cal pistol into the case...followed by tequilla shots.</font></td>
